# Robotics (engineering and research)

Framework-agnostic robotics practice. For ROS2 tooling specifics, see `ros2.mdc`.

## Modeling, frames, and units
- Use SI units everywhere; state units in names/docs. Convert at boundaries, not mid-computation.
- Right-handed coordinate frames; label every pose/twist with its reference frame and apply transforms explicitly. Never compare quantities across frames without transforming.
- Keep kinematic/dynamic parameters (link lengths, masses, inertias) in config, not hardcoded.

## Sensors and actuators
- Model sensor noise, range, and update rate; calibrate and timestamp every measurement. Account for latency and clock sync.
- Respect actuator limits (position, velocity, torque/effort); saturate commands and document the limits.

## State estimation and control
- Choose estimators deliberately (e.g. EKF/UKF/complementary) and justify the noise model. Validate against ground truth in sim.
- Specify control-loop rate and a latency budget; analyze stability and keep real-time paths free of blocking I/O and dynamic allocation.

## Safety
- Every actuator command path needs bounds checks, an estop/abort, a watchdog, and a safe default on signal loss or timeout.
- Validate sensor input before acting; reject stale or out-of-range data.

## Embedded firmware
- For microcontroller targets (e.g. MicroPython), build/flash with PlatformIO (`pio run`, `pio run -t upload`). State the hardware target explicitly.

## Simulation-first and research practice
- Validate behavior in simulation (Gazebo/Ignition, Isaac, MuJoCo) before hardware.
- Research-first: inspect existing packages, parameter files, and prior results before designing.
- Reproducibility: fix and log seeds, record configs and datasets/bags, benchmark against baselines, and report metrics (success rate, tracking error, time-to-goal).
